<br>
I used to be in the fast food business, at Dairy Queen. We had a gimp drive thru(it ran in reverse compared to most other Drive-thrus, requiring the customer to order from the driver's side, and pay from the passengers. Unfortuantely fixing this issue would require totally rebuilding the place). Oh how many times people would try to enter the drive thru in the &quot;standard&quot; direction! They'd sit there and start to pull up to the speaker and then hit the brakes and sit there....every time I pictured a big &quot;wtf?&quot; in captions above their cars with a blank stare on their faces...and how many damn times have I been told by them that it's backwards? Like I don't fuggin' KNOW THAT?!<br>
<br>
&quot;Excuse me sir, your drive-thru is backwards.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;OMG are you serious? *looks back at the drive-thru* How the hell did that happen sir? Did you see anything? Hang on I'll go get the manager.&quot;<br>
<br>
I mean really...I work there, I get told at least twice a day that it's backwards, I can SEE that it's backwards...<br>
<br>
Anyway, that's just the tip of Fast Food stupidity. The store, as do most, will run promotions sometimes. For example, the 2 for 2 dollar Single Cheeseburger and the 2 for 3 dollar Double Cheeseburger. We can have signs up EVERYWHERE around the property and people will come in, &quot;hey u got the 2 for 3?&quot; and I just wanna go &quot;No, we sold out of Double Cheeseburgers, you can only get the 2 for 2.&quot; And after the special ends(although my DQ runs 2 for 3/2 for 3 constantly) they'll come in and go &quot;Lemme get that 2 for 3&quot;. <br>
<br>
*Looks at calendar - Dec 9th* &quot;I'm sorry sir, that special ended in October.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;wtf? I just saw it on TV last week...&quot; Yeah. Right.<br>
<br>
Or while I'm on this special(bet this post ends up pretty big, I can flame about DQ customers for hours), people will come up and go:<br>
&quot;Yeah lemme get 1 Double Cheeseburger&quot;.<br>
 &quot;That'll be $2.39, please pull around&quot; *lady pulls around, I slide open door and lean out* <br>
Lady: &quot;TWO-THITTY NII` FOR ONE DOUBLE CHEESE, thought you had those on special!&quot; <br>
&quot;Yes, that's only if you buy two, then you get both for three dollars. That's why we call it a 'special'.&quot; <br>
&quot;Well, I came in here yesterday and the lady gave me 1 for a dollah-fitty&quot; <br>
&quot;I bet you did, considering it's not even POSSIBLE to ring them up like that(which it was, but involves using the coupon button but she doesn't need to know that, and the 'lady from yesterday' wouldn't've have done it either)&quot; <br>
&quot;Oh well then lemme get two I guess.&quot; <br>
&quot;Okay, that's $3.22&quot; <br>
&quot;You said they were 2 for $3, why's it $3.22?&quot; <br>
&quot;It's called 'tax', it's something the government makes you pay. Let me refer you to someone that can help you with that problem, here his name is George W. Bush, talk to him if you have any questions.&quot;<br>
<br>
So anyway -- once I had someone order a frickin' BIG MAC in Dairy Queen's drive-thru...and after McDonald's fuggin' stole the Blizzard idea from DQ(although rather poorly, McFlurries suck ass) people come in and go &quot;Yeah lemme get a Oreo McFlurry...&quot; and it's like &quot;One Orea Blizzard....&quot; Ooh I just reminded myself of the biggest gripe I have about customers when it comes to fast food....<br>
<br>
*Customer walks in*.<br>
&quot;Heya, what can I get for ya?&quot; (I'm real casual to customers, talk to em like I know em for the most part. This DQ was pretty laid back)<br>
&quot;Yes, I want an Oreo.&quot;<br>
&lt;brief pause&gt;<br>
&quot;Blizzard?&quot;<br>
&quot;Yeah.&quot;<br>
&quot;What size?&quot;<br>
&quot;Oh, uhhhh &lt;LOADING, PLEASE WAIT...&gt;Medium&quot;<br>
&quot;Aiight coo, that'll be $2.67&quot;<br>
<br>
Or<br>
<br>
&quot;Yeah lemme get a shake.&quot;<br>
&lt;brief pause&gt;<br>
&quot;What size and flavor?&quot;<br>
&lt;repeat long drawn out process of indecisive mumblings till they figure it out&gt;<br>
&quot;Aiight cool&quot;<br>
<br>
Come ON people, you can NOT SERIOUSLY expect to walk up to me and tell me that you want something and EXPECT me to know what SIZE and FLAVOR you want, can you? Am I a mind reader? If I was I wouldn't need you say dick, you could walk up, and I could punch in your entire order in under 10 seconds(cause I was that good) and go make it and all we'd have to say to each other was the total...<br>
<br>
CUSTOMERS: When you place your order, this applies to ALL places, include SIZES, FLAVORS, FOR HERE OR TO GO!!! But don't do it at light speed either, eh?<br>
<br>
I was going to include another rant here about customers and price complaints, but at the risk of sounding racist(I'm not) I am going to leave it out and end this here...I do have things to do other than flame customers...I could waste my life away on this topic.<br>
<br>
Have A Great Day all!<br>
<br>
Customer Stress Management Tip for Drive-Thru Workers: As you listen to their order, if you're headset is of a type that you have to press a button to speak into, talk evil to the customer when you release the button. It's very fun and entertaining. For example, in this format, &quot;Your voice to Customer(after you release button)&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Welcome to Fairy Queen, can I take your order(you useless piece of trash)?&quot;<br>
&quot;And what size on the large Strawberry Shake(you dumb fuck)?&quot;<br>
&quot;Okay your total is $23.49, please pull around(you ball-smoking lamer).&quot;<br>
<br>
Stuff like that(and yes, I have actually said &quot;Welcome to Fairy Queen&quot; over the speaker - too hard to tell the difference anyway) helps alot. A good laugh can cure a hundred bad customers. =)<br>
<br>
